<h1 class="hero-h">Fractional CMO <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">vs interim CMO.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Same hourly rate, sometimes. Very different intent. A fractional CMO is built to last and create compounding systems over a 6–18 month engagement. An interim CMO is built to bridge a 90–180 day gap while you search for a permanent replacement. Picking the wrong one is the cheaper false economy.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The TL;DR</span>
<h2 class="h2">The honest one-paragraph answer</h2>
<p class="body">If your previous CMO just left and you're actively searching for the permanent replacement, hire an interim CMO — full-time, expensive ($20K-$40K/month), designed to keep things running. If you're building the marketing function for the first time or you want senior leadership as an ongoing operating model (not a placeholder), hire a fractional CMO — part-time, half the monthly cost, designed to build something durable.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">What each is for</span>
<h2 class="h2">Different roles for different problems</h2>
<h3 class="h3">Interim CMO</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Time:</strong> Full-time, 5 days per week.</li>
<li><strong>Duration:</strong> 90-180 days typical; ends when permanent CMO starts.</li>
<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $20K-$40K/month all-in.</li>
<li><strong>Primary job:</strong> Stability. Keep the existing function running. Maintain team morale. Manage existing vendor relationships. Don't break anything.</li>
<li><strong>Secondary job:</strong> Sometimes participate in CMO search (less common — usually CEO + search firm own this).</li>
<li><strong>Typical context:</strong> Previous CMO departed; team has 6-15 people; the company is mid-flight on launches and campaigns that need senior coverage.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Fractional CMO</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Time:</strong> Part-time, 1-3 days per week.</li>
<li><strong>Duration:</strong> 6-18 months typical; ends when the function is durable or when a full-time CMO replaces them.</li>
<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $8K-$25K/month all-in.</li>
<li><strong>Primary job:</strong> Build. Set strategy, install systems, develop team, define KPIs, get the function producing.</li>
<li><strong>Secondary job:</strong> Often help recruit the eventual full-time hire (themselves or another).</li>
<li><strong>Typical context:</strong> No senior marketing leader currently in place; company is building marketing function for the first time or rebooting it.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Side-by-side</span>
<h2 class="h2">Direct comparison</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Interim CMO</th><th>Fractional CMO</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>Time commitment</td><td>Full-time (5 days/week)</td><td>Part-time (1-3 days/week)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Monthly cost</td><td>$20K-$40K</td><td>$8K-$25K</td></tr>
<tr><td>Typical engagement</td><td>90-180 days</td><td>6-18 months</td></tr>
<tr><td>Primary intent</td><td>Stabilize during transition</td><td>Build a durable function</td></tr>
<tr><td>Builds new systems</td><td>Rarely (don't disrupt)</td><td>Yes — primary deliverable</td></tr>
<tr><td>Team leadership</td><td>Yes — for existing team</td><td>Yes — builds or develops team</td></tr>
<tr><td>Brand + positioning work</td><td>Rare</td><td>Common</td></tr>
<tr><td>Board reporting</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>Exit transition</td><td>To permanent CMO</td><td>To full-time CMO or self-running function</td></tr>
<tr><td>Best fit company stage</td><td>Established function, departure</td><td>Building function, no senior leader</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Common confusion</span>
<h2 class="h2">Why founders mix these up</h2>
<p class="body">The market uses these terms loosely. Some "fractional CMO" providers will pitch interim work; some "interim CMO" search firms will offer fractional packaging. The labels matter less than the intent — but if you're buying the wrong intent, you'll be unhappy either way.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>The "I want interim but pay fractional prices" trap:</strong> You hire a fractional CMO at $15K/month and expect them to be available daily for the next 6 months. They aren't; they have other clients. Either you've underbought (you need interim) or you've overscoped (you need fractional working at fractional cadence).</li>
<li><strong>The "I want fractional but bought interim" trap:</strong> You hire an interim CMO at $30K/month for what you think is a permanent need. After 6 months you're spending $360K/year for someone working at maintenance mode rather than building. A fractional CMO at $180K/year would have built more.</li>
</ul>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>The diagnostic:</strong> Ask yourself, "In 12 months, is there a permanent CMO in this seat?" If yes → interim. If you're not sure → fractional. If definitely not → fractional.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Hybrid models</span>
<h2 class="h2">When the line blurs</h2>
<p class="body">Some engagements legitimately combine both shapes. Examples:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Fractional CMO scaling up temporarily.</strong> A fractional CMO at $20K/month may agree to scale up to $35K/month for 90 days during a critical launch or transition, then step back down. This works when the underlying relationship is healthy and both sides understand the temporary shape.</li>
<li><strong>Interim CMO converting to fractional.</strong> An interim CMO who lands at the right company sometimes converts the engagement to a longer fractional model once the immediate gap is bridged. Often a great outcome — the interim leader already knows the business deeply.</li>
<li><strong>Fractional-to-full-time pipeline.</strong> A fractional CMO who builds the function over 12 months becomes the leading candidate for the permanent CMO role. Common path for some firms.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

